"Thiers S., Peuportier B.","Thermal and environmental assessment of a passive building equipped with an earth-to-air heat exchanger in France",2008,"Solar Energy","82","9",,"820","831",,,10.1016/j.solener.2008.02.014,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-47749103747&partnerID=40&md5=954eae48f4b0b1b46557c6eec63e6315","Centre Énergétique et Procédés, École des Mines de Paris, 60 Bd Saint-Michel, 75272 Paris Cedex 06, France","Thiers, S., Centre Énergétique et Procédés, École des Mines de Paris, 60 Bd Saint-Michel, 75272 Paris Cedex 06, France; Peuportier, B., Centre Énergétique et Procédés, École des Mines de Paris, 60 Bd Saint-Michel, 75272 Paris Cedex 06, France","In France, where a division by 4 of the greenhouse gases emissions is aimed from 1990 to 2050, technical solutions are studied in order to reduce energy consumption while providing a satisfactory thermal comfort level in buildings. A two-dwelling passive building has been carried out in Formerie (North-West of France), complying the ""Passivhaus"" standard. This building, not yet monitored, has been modeled using the dynamic simulation software COMFIE, which is dedicated to building eco-design. In order to account for the implemented ventilation system, including a heat recovery unit and an earth-to-air heat exchanger, a specific model has been developed and integrated to COMFIE as a new module. In this article, this model is described first. In order to quantify the benefits brought by a passive design, the simulation results are presented for the passive house and a reference house complying with the French thermal regulation for buildings. The heating load and thermal comfort level of both houses are compared, showing for the passive design a tenfold reduction of the heating load and a clear reduction of summer discomfort. Finally, the environmental assessment - carried out with the life cycle assessment tool EQUER - shows the reduction in primary energy consumption, global warming potential and other impacts brought by the passive house design. Passive house appears to be an adequate solution to improve the environmental performances of buildings in the French context. © 2008 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Earth-to-air heat exchanger; Life cycle assessment; Passive house; Thermal simulation","Air pollution; Buildings; Computer simulation; Energy policy; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Heat exchangers; Heating; Houses; Life cycle; Software design; Solar water heaters; Solutions; Standards; Thermal comfort; Ventilation; Waste heat; dynamic simulations; Eco designs; Elsevier (CO); Energy consumption; Environmental assessment (ES); Environmental performance (EP); Global-warming potential (GWP); Green House Gases emission; Heat recovery unit (HRU); Heating loads; In buildings; In order; Life cycle assessment (LCA)); Passive design; Passive houses; Primary energy consumption; simulation results; Technical solutions; Ventilation systems; Energy conservation; building; energy conservation; energy use; environmental assessment; greenhouse gas; life cycle analysis; software; ventilation; Eurasia; Europe; France; Western Europe",,,,,,"Al Ajmi, F., Loveday, D.L., Hanby, V.I., The cooling potential of earth-air heat exchangers for domestic buildings in a desert climate (2005) Building and Environment, 41, pp. 235-244; Bacot, P., Neveu, A., Sicard, J., Analyse modale des phénomènes thermiques en régime variable dans le bâtiment (1984) Revue Générale de Thermique, 267, pp. 189-201. , (in French); Badescu, V., Simple and accurate model for the ground heat exchanger of a passive house (2007) Renewable energy, 32, pp. 845-855; Benkert, S., Heidt, F.D., 2000. Abschlussbericht zum Projekt: Validierung des Programms ""Graphische Auslegung von ErdwärmeAustauschern GAEA"" mit Hilfe von Messdaten im Rahmen des Verbundprojekts ""Luft-/Erdwärme tauscher"" der AG Solar NRW. FG Bauphysik & Solarenergie, University of Siegen, Germany (in German). <http://nesa1.uni-siege